ndency API types could violate guidelines. Our test creates a class as a byte fixture, but I’m unsure if that’s acceptable since it mimics the real package. If we use an actual Gradle launcher jar as a test dependency, it could be a better approach. I might need to explore other options, like Gradle build variables and their version-agnostic nature. However, I’m worried if it may call System.exit during execution.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Assessing GradleMain dependencies**\\n\\nI’m looking at how the `URLClassLoader` only includes the gradle-launcher jar and the parent platform, which means that the real GradleMain might fail due to NoClassDefFoundError for missing dependencies. If I attempt to load classes or methods, I’ll face a situation where Method.invoke is called, but could still lead to errors. I need to catch any expected InvocationTargetExceptions that arise, since Method.invoke wraps them as Errors. This makes starting the process complex since it throws various exceptions.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring jar creation**\\n\\nI’m considering producing a jar with a class name using Byte Buddy, but it feels a bit fake. The actual public API requires dynamic loading for the class. I wonder if tests can use a fixture for an external plugin implementation? The rule states no stubs or shadow classes should be on the test classpath. I seem to be in a temporary jar, simulating an external Gradle distribution, which I think I’d want to keep.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_eChjC9cZUi0Lv6kF8eXJWeXE|fc_08a809a073601555016a426755ca308196a80dc431c9efabdd", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.quarkus/quarkus-bootstrap-gradle-resolver/3.33.1/src/test/java/io_quarkus/quarkus_bootstrap_gradle_resolver/OrgGradleWrapperBootstrapMainStarterTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "    private static final String GRADLE_MAIN_CLASS_ENTRY = \"org/gradle/launcher/GradleMain.class\";\n    private static final String GRADLE_